1) Debouncing 
Debouncing = Pause the function (like API call) until the user stops typing.
It pauses the frequently call api.

When user trying to search something on search box and user removes the cursor then api will call so till that time api call pause.
in Debauncing function every time we clear the previous timeout.and start new timer every time

Debauncing is the technique that is ensures the functions are not called rapidly.
it ensures the functions are not Triggered rapidly.
it execute the functions only once after 
it execute the functions only once after specific time period .
It send Api request when user stops the interacting with the page.



function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timer;
  return function (...args) {
    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => {
      func.apply(this, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}

// Usage
const handleInput = debounce(() => {
  console.log("Search triggered!");
}, 300);

document.getElementById("searchBox").addEventListener("input", handleInput);

 Step-by-Step Breakdown
 ----------------------------------------
1. function debounce(func, delay)
You pass in:
func: the function you want to delay (like an AJAX call).
delay: how long to wait (in milliseconds) after the last event.
2. let timer;
This stores the ID of the timeout so we can cancel it if needed.
3. return function (...args)
This returns a new function that wraps your original func.
...args means it can accept any number of arguments (like search term, event, etc.).
4. clearTimeout(timer);
If the user types again before the delay is over, cancel the previous timer.
5. timer = setTimeout(() => { ... }, delay);
Start a new timer. If no new input comes in during the delay, the function inside will run.
6. func.apply(this, args);
This is where your original function (func) is finally called.
apply(this, args):
this: keeps the correct context (important if you're using this inside func)
args: passes all the original arguments to func


