4) javascript execution phase
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-> JavaScript runs in two main phases:
    i) Creation Phase (Memory Allocation)
        -------------------------------------------
        The JavaScript engine scans the code.
        Variables and functions are hoisted.
        Variables declared with var are initialized with undefined.
        Functions (declared with function) are fully hoisted.
        let and const are hoisted but stay in the Temporal Dead Zone (TDZ) until their definition is reached.
    ii) Execution Phase
        -------------------------------
        Code is executed line by line.
        Values are assigned, functions are invoked, and expressions are evaluated.

    Call Stack
    ------------
        The Call Stack is where JavaScript keeps track of function calls.
        It's LIFO (Last In, First Out).
        When a function is called, it's pushed onto the stack.
        When it finishes, it's popped off.

        example
        ----------------------------
        
        function greet() {
        console.log("Hello");
        }

        function start() {
        greet();
        }

        start();

        start() → greet() → console.log()

   
    
    Event Loop
    --------------------
        The Event Loop is the mechanism that checks if the Call Stack is empty, and if so, it pushes tasks from the Task Queue or Microtask Queue to the stack


    Web APIs (Browser APIs)
    --------------------------------------
            The web api are handled by browser when call stack sees the web apis then it send to browser so browser will handle by browser

            Examples:
            ---------------------
            i) setTimeout
            ii) DOM events
            iii) fetch
            iv) localStorage
                When you use something like setTimeout, it goes to the Web API environment, not the call stack.

    Task Queue (Macrotasks) (Low priority)
    -----------------------------
        setTimeout
        setInterval
        I/O tasks
    Microtask Queue(High priority)
    ------------------------
        Promises
        MutationObserver

    Example
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    
        console.log("Start");

        setTimeout(() => {
        console.log("Macrotask");
        }, 0);

        Promise.resolve().then(() => {
        console.log("Microtask");
        });

        console.log("End");
    
    Start and End are synchronous → executed immediately.
    Promise.then() → goes to Microtask Queue.
    setTimeout() → goes to Macrotask Queue.
    After the synchronous code finishes, Microtasks are executed.
    Then the Macrotask is executed.


